00:04:03.550 --> 00:04:07.450
So today I want to talk about a
subset of solutions, and in

00:04:07.450 --> 00:04:09.410
particular, I want to talk
about acids and bases.

00:04:09.410 --> 00:04:12.230
And this is important, not only
in materials processing,

00:04:12.230 --> 00:04:13.747
but we're going to have to
understand this if we're going

00:04:13.747 --> 00:04:17.040
to go forward later and talk
about biochemistry.

00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:19.100
So, you know, they're around
us everywhere.

00:04:19.100 --> 00:04:21.060
You know, you probably got up
this morning, you washed your

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:23.980
hair with a pH-balanced shampoo,
maybe had orange

00:04:23.980 --> 00:04:27.460
juice or grapefruit juice with
citric and ascorbic acid.

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:30.600
Your radio is powered by zinc
alkaline batteries.

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:34.400
I started my car, it's got the
lead acid battery in it, and

00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:36.450
electricity for all my
appliances came from

00:04:36.450 --> 00:04:39.020
coal-fired power plants,
spewing out SO2,

00:04:39.020 --> 00:04:40.590
turning out acid rain.

00:04:40.590 --> 00:04:41.580
So we're off to a good start!

00:04:41.580 --> 00:04:43.260
It's Friday.

00:04:43.260 --> 00:04:45.000
So now we want to go
back and understand

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:46.230
this from the beginning.

00:04:46.230 --> 00:04:48.135
So we're going to start
with a history lesson.

00:04:48.135 --> 00:04:51.520
And the history lesson starts
in ancient times.

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:56.350
Acids were known all the way
back in early times for

00:04:56.350 --> 00:04:59.856
processing of food
and materials.

00:05:07.790 --> 00:05:10.530
So who among us hasn't
eaten something

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:11.600
that has been pickled?

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:16.130
Pickle means to have been
processed in acid solution.

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:20.890
In fact, the word acid comes
from the word acidus in Latin,

00:05:20.890 --> 00:05:24.265
and acidus means either
sour or tart.

00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:32.360
But the modern chemistry of
acids and bases starts with

00:05:32.360 --> 00:05:38.475
Lavoisier in France in 1779.

00:05:38.475 --> 00:05:42.260
And I'm going to be naming many
scientists from different

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:44.180
countries today, so I'm
going to use the

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:45.800
international symbol.

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:48.310
You know, these ovals that you
put on the back of the car, so

00:05:48.310 --> 00:05:50.360
now if you see a car with
this on it, you know

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:51.970
it's a French registry.

00:05:51.970 --> 00:05:54.140
So he's probably got a Peugeot,
and he's driving

00:05:54.140 --> 00:05:55.500
around with his Peugeot.

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:59.640
And what Lavoisier said, in
trying to understand acids and

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:00.680
bases, is--

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:03.290
it's a really interesting
story.

00:06:03.290 --> 00:06:06.997
He said that oxygen is
present in all acids.

00:06:17.650 --> 00:06:18.780
And why?

00:06:18.780 --> 00:06:21.500
Because he spent most of his
career studying combustion, so

00:06:21.500 --> 00:06:24.510
he was very concerned
about oxygen.

00:06:24.510 --> 00:06:30.240
And the interesting thing is
that oxygen, the name of the

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:34.920
gas, oxygen, actually comes
from the greek oxy, which

00:06:34.920 --> 00:06:39.380
means sharp, and, you know,
the particle gen, as in to

00:06:39.380 --> 00:06:41.290
generate or to be born.

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:42.540
OK?

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:49.540
So it's interesting that this
gas is named incorrectly.

00:06:49.540 --> 00:06:55.110
It's named for an attribute that
is ascribed to acid, and

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:57.210
it's wrong.

00:06:57.210 --> 00:06:58.710
And it's in other
languages, too.

00:06:58.710 --> 00:07:01.890
The word oxygen translates
into other languages as

00:07:01.890 --> 00:07:04.340
meaning something sharp, and it
has nothing to do with it.

00:07:04.340 --> 00:07:07.500
But while we're on the topic
of Lavoisier, Lavoisier did

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:10.030
study oxygen.

00:07:10.030 --> 00:07:15.620
And there was an intense rivalry
between Lavoisier in

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:21.950
France, Joseph Priestley
in Britain,

00:07:21.950 --> 00:07:26.000
and Scheele in Sweden.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:29.460
And all three of them were
working simultaneously to

00:07:29.460 --> 00:07:33.680
study combustion and
understand oxygen.

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:35.970
And here I've got a
very nice image.

00:07:35.970 --> 00:07:40.290
This is a portrait of Lavoisier
with his wife.

00:07:40.290 --> 00:07:42.440
And it's hard to see.

00:07:42.440 --> 00:07:45.460
If the lights were a little
bit dimmer, you'd see--

00:07:45.460 --> 00:07:48.540
notice here, you see all of
this chemical apparatus.

00:07:48.540 --> 00:07:53.400
There is bell jars, and various
glass apparatus.

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:57.270
His wife was his partner
in the laboratory.

00:07:57.270 --> 00:07:59.350
She was unique among
French women in

00:07:59.350 --> 00:08:01.920
that she read English.

00:08:01.920 --> 00:08:05.600
And in his rivalry with
Priestley, he relied on his

00:08:05.600 --> 00:08:08.660
wife in order to read
Priestley's writings.

00:08:08.660 --> 00:08:09.530
So they worked together.

00:08:09.530 --> 00:08:12.960
She even helped him
in the laboratory.

00:08:12.960 --> 00:08:17.020
They married at the time he
was 27 and she was 13, and

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:17.720
they were--

00:08:17.720 --> 00:08:18.960
what are you so shocked about?

00:08:18.960 --> 00:08:23.650
It's France, and it's 1779!

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:24.580
Get over it!

00:08:24.580 --> 00:08:28.720
Anyways, she helped him a lot,
and we'll say a little bit

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:32.590
more about that later.

00:08:32.590 --> 00:08:32.930
OK.

00:08:32.930 --> 00:08:36.370
So now let's go on to the next
part of the history lesson.

00:08:36.370 --> 00:08:39.740
So so far, we've got one
explanation, and it's wrong.

00:08:39.740 --> 00:08:42.340
So let's go to the next one,
and we'll go to Britain.

00:08:42.340 --> 00:08:47.230
Sir Humphry Davy in
London in 1810.

00:08:47.230 --> 00:08:50.240
So we'll put GB here, and he's
driving around in his little

00:08:50.240 --> 00:08:51.740
Jaguar, I suspect.

00:08:51.740 --> 00:08:53.560
And he said something
that was correct.

00:08:53.560 --> 00:08:57.000
He said that it's hydrogen
present in all acids.

00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:03.750
And that was pretty much it.

00:09:03.750 --> 00:09:06.290
He was a great scientist, did
some very good work, but

00:09:06.290 --> 00:09:08.450
really didn't do anything
quantitative here.

00:09:08.450 --> 00:09:11.600
So for the quantitative stuff,
we have to wait for almost the

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:12.980
end of the century.

00:09:12.980 --> 00:09:15.240
And we go up to Sweden
again, to Arrhenius.

00:09:15.240 --> 00:09:19.590
And Arrhenius, in 1887--

00:09:19.590 --> 00:09:21.300
so I'll give him a Volvo.

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:26.750
And he said that the acid is a
substance that disassociates

00:09:26.750 --> 00:09:28.740
to produce protons.

00:09:28.740 --> 00:09:37.940
So the acid is defined as a
solution that dissociates to

00:09:37.940 --> 00:09:40.410
give protons.

00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:44.540
I'm going to say H plus, meaning
the hydrogen ion, or P

00:09:44.540 --> 00:09:47.770
plus, and we're going to keep
using the term proton.

00:09:47.770 --> 00:09:50.560
I'm not going to say hydrogen
ion, I'm going to say proton.

00:09:50.560 --> 00:09:51.890
So proton in solution.

00:09:51.890 --> 00:09:53.370
So this is what he defines.

00:09:53.370 --> 00:09:55.270
And he further defines
the base.

00:09:55.270 --> 00:09:58.800
He defines the base as the
complement to the acid.

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:02.420
And he says that the base is
something that dissociates to

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:04.360
give us hydroxyl.

00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:12.380
The base dissociates to give
OH minus the hydroxyl.

00:10:12.380 --> 00:10:17.220
And so now we've got this whole
concept of electrolytic

00:10:17.220 --> 00:10:21.530
disassociation, which is what
wins him the Nobel prize in

00:10:21.530 --> 00:10:23.690
1903 for this thing.

00:10:23.690 --> 00:10:27.800
And then we saw last day how the
addition of ions to water

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:29.050
gives charge carriers.

00:10:29.050 --> 00:10:33.350
And so the presence of protons
and hydroxyl is, in fact, the

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:37.350
way we have any charge carried
through water.

00:10:37.350 --> 00:10:40.450
So up until now, when I said
electrical conductivity, we

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:43.830
were pretty much referring to
electronic conductivity.

00:10:43.830 --> 00:10:46.740
But there's a second kind of
conductivity, and we can have

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:49.500
ionic conductivity.

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:52.900
Ionic conductivity, as the
name implies, is not by

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:54.730
electrons, but by ions.

00:10:54.730 --> 00:10:56.915
And this is typically
ions in solution.

00:11:00.190 --> 00:11:03.820
Ionic conductivity in solution,
and a solution that

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:06.165
is an ionic conductor is
called an electrolyte.

00:11:08.910 --> 00:11:10.740
So we have electrolyte
in our bodies,

00:11:10.740 --> 00:11:14.290
saline, about 5% chloride.

00:11:14.290 --> 00:11:16.730
We have electrolyte in batteries
that are ionically

00:11:16.730 --> 00:11:17.930
conductive.

00:11:17.930 --> 00:11:23.160
And the term simply means, we
have conduction by ions.

00:11:23.160 --> 00:11:27.390
And so it was the theory of
electrolytic dissociation that

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:30.030
won the Nobel prize.

00:11:30.030 --> 00:11:32.260
So how does this work?

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:36.230
So we can start with something
like HCl gas.

00:11:36.230 --> 00:11:39.540
I'm going to dissolve it in
water, and this will give me

00:11:39.540 --> 00:11:41.155
proton, H plus.

00:11:41.155 --> 00:11:44.940
And I'm going to write aq,
meaning that it's dissolved in

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:50.120
water, and the chloride ion,
also dissolved in water.

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:52.920
And so this gives me an acid.

00:11:52.920 --> 00:11:55.130
This is a proton donor.

00:11:55.130 --> 00:11:56.030
And now let's look at

00:11:56.030 --> 00:11:58.380
something like sodium hydroxide.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:00.800
Sodium hydroxide at room
temperature is an ionic

00:12:00.800 --> 00:12:05.440
compound, so it is a solid, but
it is soluble in a polar,

00:12:05.440 --> 00:12:13.420
hydrogen-bonded liquid, so H20,
to give hydroxyl aqueous

00:12:13.420 --> 00:12:16.700
plus sodium ion aqueous.

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:19.270
So again, we see the
dissociation.

00:12:19.270 --> 00:12:21.800
And then we can have,
from here, a

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:24.240
neutralization reaction.

00:12:24.240 --> 00:12:26.740
And the neutralization
reaction is simply

00:12:26.740 --> 00:12:29.520
reconstitution of the solvent.

00:12:29.520 --> 00:12:33.870
So neutralization, another way
to think about it, because

00:12:33.870 --> 00:12:36.300
we're not going to be confined
to water by the end of the

00:12:36.300 --> 00:12:40.340
lecture, neutralization is
simply a reaction that results

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:44.230
in reconstitution
of the solvents.

00:12:44.230 --> 00:12:46.330
So the solvent, in this
case, is water.

00:12:46.330 --> 00:12:48.260
So how would we reconstitute
water?

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:50.520
We combine proton
with hydroxyl.

00:12:50.520 --> 00:12:55.110
So let's do that and see the
result of that reaction.

00:12:55.110 --> 00:13:00.360
So if I take, and run it in the
vertical direction, proton

00:13:00.360 --> 00:13:05.130
plus hydroxyl, we'll
give water again--

00:13:05.130 --> 00:13:07.580
let's give H20 liquid--

00:13:07.580 --> 00:13:11.080
and now you can see Na
plus Cl will give me

00:13:11.080 --> 00:13:14.310
NaCl, aqueous dissolved.

00:13:14.310 --> 00:13:16.590
So this is what you probably
learned in your high school

00:13:16.590 --> 00:13:21.230
chemistry, that acid plus base
ca give you salt plus water.

00:13:21.230 --> 00:13:24.910
So you see all of this resulting
from just the simple

00:13:24.910 --> 00:13:26.640
Arrhenius definition.

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:27.580
So this is good.

00:13:27.580 --> 00:13:30.800
We've got off to a decent start
here with Arrhenius.

00:13:30.800 --> 00:13:34.470
But then the theory has its
limitations, as they all do.

00:13:34.470 --> 00:13:36.420
And how do we discover
the limitations?

00:13:36.420 --> 00:13:37.860
With some new data.

00:13:37.860 --> 00:13:39.460
So let's look at some data.

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:45.950
So it had been known for a long
time that ammonia, when

00:13:45.950 --> 00:13:50.950
it's dissolved in water, can act
as a solution capable of

00:13:50.950 --> 00:13:52.840
neutralizing an acid.

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:55.780
So if ammonia dissolved in water
neutralizes an acid,

00:13:55.780 --> 00:13:56.845
then this must be a base.

00:13:56.845 --> 00:13:59.290
But look, there's no
hydroxyl here.

00:13:59.290 --> 00:14:01.910
So the Arrhenius definition
of base is inadequate

00:14:01.910 --> 00:14:03.630
to account for this.

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:04.910
So let's just get that down.

00:14:04.910 --> 00:14:08.750
Ammonia, which you know is a gas
at room temperature, will

00:14:08.750 --> 00:14:15.520
neutralize acids.

00:14:15.520 --> 00:14:20.020
But no hydroxyl present.

00:14:20.020 --> 00:14:24.980
So something's going on here
that we can't account for by

00:14:24.980 --> 00:14:26.950
the simple Arrhenius
definition.

00:14:26.950 --> 00:14:30.020
So to get us out of this
conundrum, we had to wait

00:14:30.020 --> 00:14:31.410
until 1923.

00:14:31.410 --> 00:14:34.620
And two scientists
simultaneously enunciated the

00:14:34.620 --> 00:14:35.560
same ideas.

00:14:35.560 --> 00:14:37.640
So I'm going to put
them both down.

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:38.680
1923.

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:44.850
Bronsted, who was in Denmark,
and Lowry, who was

00:14:44.850 --> 00:14:46.800
working in the UK.

00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:50.830
Also 1923.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:53.380
And I'll give him a
Jaguar as well.

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:56.540
And so the two of them proposed
a broader definition

00:14:56.540 --> 00:14:58.790
to account for what's
going on here.

00:14:58.790 --> 00:14:59.710
And what did they say?

00:14:59.710 --> 00:15:01.640
They said that acid--

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:04.630
they'll keep the same definition
as Arrhenius.

00:15:04.630 --> 00:15:07.280
So an acid is going to
be a proton donor.

00:15:10.240 --> 00:15:11.300
So that's good.

00:15:11.300 --> 00:15:14.780
Let's even put here,
same as Arrhenius.

00:15:18.150 --> 00:15:19.830
But now here's the difference.

00:15:19.830 --> 00:15:24.500
The base is no longer confined
to hydroxyl chemistry.

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:26.710
They call it a proton
acceptor.

00:15:30.140 --> 00:15:31.970
And that's different.

00:15:31.970 --> 00:15:35.530
So hydroxyl-free.

00:15:35.530 --> 00:15:37.470
Now, let's be careful here.

00:15:37.470 --> 00:15:39.630
If I propose this new
definition, I

00:15:39.630 --> 00:15:40.970
can't throw out hydroxyl.

00:15:40.970 --> 00:15:43.990
So you've got to watch to make
sure that by broadening the

00:15:43.990 --> 00:15:46.030
definition, we don't
exclude hydroxyl.

00:15:46.030 --> 00:15:49.650
So the theory has to encompass
what we already know, and then

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:53.350
continue to encompass things
that tend to contradict what

00:15:53.350 --> 00:15:54.060
we already know.

00:15:54.060 --> 00:15:56.540
So let's take a look at
what this gives us.

00:15:56.540 --> 00:16:01.750
So I'm going to write a
broader equation here.

00:16:01.750 --> 00:16:06.180
I'm going to write
this as the acid.

00:16:06.180 --> 00:16:07.290
So what do I have?

00:16:07.290 --> 00:16:10.180
I have every acid has
to have a proton in

00:16:10.180 --> 00:16:12.100
it, plus some residual.

00:16:12.100 --> 00:16:15.380
So I can rewrite the
acid in this form.

00:16:15.380 --> 00:16:18.990
I'm going to react
it with a base.

00:16:18.990 --> 00:16:21.300
So according to this definition,
this has to be a

00:16:21.300 --> 00:16:23.170
proton donor.

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:25.060
And this, you're going to
watch me on this one.

00:16:25.060 --> 00:16:27.390
This is going to be
a proton acceptor.

00:16:27.390 --> 00:16:28.690
And we'll put some
identities here.

00:16:28.690 --> 00:16:30.520
Eventually we're going to write
this with ammonia in it,

00:16:30.520 --> 00:16:32.850
but let's just do the
broad definition.

00:16:32.850 --> 00:16:36.200
So what happens is, if this is
a proton acceptor, on this

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:38.820
side of the equation, it takes
the proton from here.

00:16:38.820 --> 00:16:40.010
This is the proton donor.

00:16:40.010 --> 00:16:45.130
It gives it away, and we
end up with a BH plus.

00:16:45.130 --> 00:16:48.400
So this proton acceptor has
accepted the proton, leaving

00:16:48.400 --> 00:16:52.660
behind the deprotonated
A minus.

00:16:52.660 --> 00:16:54.260
That's a nice little reaction.

00:16:54.260 --> 00:16:57.850
But now, if you'd nodded off for
the last 90 seconds, and

00:16:57.850 --> 00:17:01.010
then opened your eyes and said,
well, he said acid is a

00:17:01.010 --> 00:17:04.460
proton donor, this thing
can give up a proton.

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:08.090
So OK, I'm going to call this
thing a proton donor.

00:17:08.090 --> 00:17:10.410
And this is most certainly
a proton acceptor.

00:17:10.410 --> 00:17:12.660
Look, it has accepted
the proton.

00:17:12.660 --> 00:17:16.890
So this is going to be
a proton acceptor.

00:17:16.890 --> 00:17:20.050
So now I've got in this equation
two proton donors and

00:17:20.050 --> 00:17:21.910
two proton acceptors.

00:17:21.910 --> 00:17:23.160
And they're linked.

00:17:23.160 --> 00:17:26.660
This proton donor, BH plus,
is linked to B.

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:30.360
So I'm going to put a little
yolk over this one.

00:17:30.360 --> 00:17:34.200
And this HA, the original
acid, is linked to

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:36.630
this base, A minus.

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:38.425
So I'm going to put
a yoke over that.

00:17:41.430 --> 00:17:47.730
And the Latin word for yoke, to
yoke, is jugere, from which

00:17:47.730 --> 00:17:50.350
we get the word conjugate.

00:17:50.350 --> 00:17:52.560
So I'm going to call
these things

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:54.665
conjugate acid-base pairs.

00:18:02.050 --> 00:18:04.770
And every equation has two.

00:18:04.770 --> 00:18:06.840
Because you've got a proton
donor proton acceptor.

00:18:06.840 --> 00:18:09.130
So now this is, follow
the bouncing ball.

00:18:09.130 --> 00:18:11.880
If you want to understand
acid-base chemistry, just

00:18:11.880 --> 00:18:12.950
follow the proton.

00:18:12.950 --> 00:18:15.100
Here's proton here,
goes over here.

00:18:15.100 --> 00:18:18.980
Here's something deprotonated,
now it's protonated.

00:18:18.980 --> 00:18:22.130
That's the rhythm here.

00:18:22.130 --> 00:18:27.250
So the whole thing is, acid-base
reactions can be

00:18:27.250 --> 00:18:29.965
defined as a proton transfer
reactions.

00:18:33.500 --> 00:18:37.590
Remember we talked about
ionicity and electron transfer

00:18:37.590 --> 00:18:40.090
in order to achieve
octet stability?

00:18:40.090 --> 00:18:42.140
So we saw the whole
life and times of

00:18:42.140 --> 00:18:43.600
electron transfer reactions.

00:18:43.600 --> 00:18:47.470
Now life and times of proton
transfer reactions.

00:18:47.470 --> 00:18:47.840
OK.

00:18:47.840 --> 00:18:50.710
And last thing I want to do, is
to just make sure that we

00:18:50.710 --> 00:18:52.360
see the definitions.

00:18:52.360 --> 00:18:55.870
You know, all queens are female,
but not all females

00:18:55.870 --> 00:18:56.950
are queens.

00:18:56.950 --> 00:18:59.200
So this one here, what's this?

00:18:59.200 --> 00:19:01.840
This is definitely, it's
a proton donor.

00:19:01.840 --> 00:19:02.990
So it's an acid.

00:19:02.990 --> 00:19:06.350
So it's definitely an Arrhenius
acid, because it's

00:19:06.350 --> 00:19:11.850
got a proton, and it's also
a Bronsted-Lowry acid.

00:19:11.850 --> 00:19:14.270
Now, what about this one?

00:19:14.270 --> 00:19:15.510
This is a base.

00:19:15.510 --> 00:19:17.690
It may not have hydroxyl
in it.

00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:18.670
May or may not.

00:19:18.670 --> 00:19:22.580
So this is definitely a
Bronsted-Lowry base, but I

00:19:22.580 --> 00:19:25.730
can't say for sure that it's
an Arrhenius base, because

00:19:25.730 --> 00:19:28.100
Arrhenius has to be O minus.

00:19:28.100 --> 00:19:29.460
This one here, what
about this?

00:19:29.460 --> 00:19:33.310
Unless it's OH minus, this
one here is, what?

00:19:33.310 --> 00:19:36.950
It's Bronsted-Lowry base.

00:19:36.950 --> 00:19:41.010
And this one here, this can be
both Bronsted-Lowry acid and

00:19:41.010 --> 00:19:44.070
it can be an Arrhenius acid.

00:19:44.070 --> 00:19:47.940
So this is how we can
differentiate them.

00:19:47.940 --> 00:19:50.400
OK, good.

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:53.920
Now let's go to the ammonia, see
if we've got ourselves out

00:19:53.920 --> 00:19:57.330
of the conundrum so we
can write now NH3.

00:19:57.330 --> 00:19:58.920
And I'm going to say that
this is ammonia

00:19:58.920 --> 00:20:00.320
that's already dissolved.

00:20:00.320 --> 00:20:04.020
So ammonia is already in aqueous
solution, and it

00:20:04.020 --> 00:20:10.170
reacts with water, H20
liquid, to do what?

00:20:10.170 --> 00:20:12.250
This is supposed to be a--

00:20:12.250 --> 00:20:16.390
if this is a base, remember,
this is the thing that we're

00:20:16.390 --> 00:20:17.390
trying to demonstrate.

00:20:17.390 --> 00:20:20.180
If it's a base, according to
this, it's a proton acceptor.

00:20:20.180 --> 00:20:22.920
So I'm going to stick a proton
on this, and I'm going to get

00:20:22.920 --> 00:20:26.450
NH4 plus the ammonium ion.

00:20:29.010 --> 00:20:30.940
And how did I get the
ammonium ion?

00:20:30.940 --> 00:20:36.950
I took a proton from water,
leaving behind OH.

00:20:36.950 --> 00:20:39.480
So can you see that how
this thing works?

00:20:39.480 --> 00:20:43.430
By gobbling up protons, by
becoming a proton vacuum

00:20:43.430 --> 00:20:48.020
cleaner, it takes protons
out of water, leaving

00:20:48.020 --> 00:20:49.630
an excess of hydroxyl.

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:52.710
And in effect, now we've got
something that's tantamount to

00:20:52.710 --> 00:20:54.030
an Arrhenius base.

00:20:54.030 --> 00:20:55.930
But it all started
off with this.

00:20:55.930 --> 00:20:57.760
So now we can link these two.

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:02.300
I'm going to yoke ammonium
and ammonia as conjugate

00:21:02.300 --> 00:21:05.280
acid-base, and there is
water and hydroxyl

00:21:05.280 --> 00:21:06.850
as acid-base pairs.

00:21:06.850 --> 00:21:10.770
So again, let's get
the colors going.

00:21:10.770 --> 00:21:12.460
Here we've got Bronsted-Lowry--

00:21:12.460 --> 00:21:14.380
the bases are always going
to be in blue.

00:21:14.380 --> 00:21:16.340
Blue and base both begin
with the letter B.

00:21:16.340 --> 00:21:19.950
So this is definitely
Brosted-Lowry base, but it's

00:21:19.950 --> 00:21:22.110
not an Arrhenius base.

00:21:22.110 --> 00:21:26.100
This is a Bronsted-Lowry
base, and it's also

00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:28.570
an Arrhenius base.

00:21:28.570 --> 00:21:31.160
This one here, we can
call this one--

00:21:31.160 --> 00:21:35.000
in this case, it's a proton
donor, so it's both an

00:21:35.000 --> 00:21:37.880
Arrhenius acid and a
Bronsted-Lowry acid.

00:21:37.880 --> 00:21:38.760
But look at this.

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:41.740
You'd say, OK, I know
what he's doing.

00:21:41.740 --> 00:21:44.760
Arrheius, Bronsted-Lowry,
Arrhenius, Bronsted-Lowry.

00:21:44.760 --> 00:21:47.170
This is Bronsted-Lowry
only, this must be

00:21:47.170 --> 00:21:48.420
Bronsted-Lowry only.

00:21:48.420 --> 00:21:49.070
But look!

00:21:49.070 --> 00:21:51.540
This is a proton donor.

00:21:51.540 --> 00:21:53.100
It dissociates to
give protons.

00:21:53.100 --> 00:21:57.420
So this is both Bronsted-Lowry
and Arrhenius.

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:59.640
Most people will miss that.

00:21:59.640 --> 00:22:03.410
We'll get to see, maybe, on a
subsequent celebration, how

00:22:03.410 --> 00:22:05.370
many of you miss that.

00:22:05.370 --> 00:22:05.680
OK.

00:22:05.680 --> 00:22:06.330
So.

00:22:06.330 --> 00:22:08.570
So now, let's go into
the chemistry here.

00:22:08.570 --> 00:22:11.730
Because I said up here at the
beginning of the lecture--

00:22:11.730 --> 00:22:14.740
what is it-- bonding is the
key to understanding.

00:22:14.740 --> 00:22:18.030
So what is it about bonding
here that defines the

00:22:18.030 --> 00:22:19.310
Bronsted-Lowry base?

00:22:19.310 --> 00:22:23.240
So I'm going to write this
reaction in this way, now.

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:25.810
I'm going to put-- here's
the proton, which

00:22:25.810 --> 00:22:27.220
is coming from water.

00:22:27.220 --> 00:22:29.290
And I'm going to write
that with NH3.

00:22:29.290 --> 00:22:31.610
I'm going to use the
Lewis structure.

00:22:31.610 --> 00:22:35.730
So, you know, Lewis structure
looks like this, Nitrate has

00:22:35.730 --> 00:22:39.380
got five valence electrons,
three of them are bound, and

00:22:39.380 --> 00:22:41.010
now I've got this long pair.

00:22:41.010 --> 00:22:45.580
So what do we know about
the electronic

00:22:45.580 --> 00:22:46.960
structure of proton?

00:22:46.960 --> 00:22:47.770
What does it look like?

00:22:47.770 --> 00:22:49.020
What's the Lewis structure
of proton?

00:22:52.080 --> 00:22:54.480
How many electrons on proton?

00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:54.900
None.

00:22:54.900 --> 00:22:56.680
This is nothing.

00:22:56.680 --> 00:22:59.520
This is very needy.

00:22:59.520 --> 00:23:02.910
It's like the neediest friend
you have. You know, the one

00:23:02.910 --> 00:23:05.530
that's always taking stuff
from you, taking your

00:23:05.530 --> 00:23:08.950
emotional energy, giving
back nothing?

00:23:08.950 --> 00:23:10.180
That's proton.

00:23:10.180 --> 00:23:12.100
That's the human equivalent
of proton.

00:23:12.100 --> 00:23:17.310
So if proton wants to make a
bond to form NH4, proton is

00:23:17.310 --> 00:23:22.590
going to come over here and
exploit both electrons.

00:23:22.590 --> 00:23:26.700
So if this is going to be a
proton acceptor, the only way

00:23:26.700 --> 00:23:30.000
it can be a proton acceptor
is to have two

00:23:30.000 --> 00:23:32.130
unused electrons available.

00:23:32.130 --> 00:23:34.520
This is going to be a
dative bond, agreed?

00:23:34.520 --> 00:23:37.450
Dative, because both electrons
from the bond

00:23:37.450 --> 00:23:38.780
come from the nitrogen.

00:23:38.780 --> 00:23:41.510
The proton doesn't contribute
anything.

00:23:41.510 --> 00:23:43.060
So that's the hallmark.

00:23:43.060 --> 00:23:49.900
The proton acceptor
axiomatically must have an

00:23:49.900 --> 00:23:53.480
available non-bonding pair.

00:23:53.480 --> 00:23:59.660
So wherever you see non-bonding
pairs, wherever

00:23:59.660 --> 00:24:03.010
you see a compound that has
this capability, it could

00:24:03.010 --> 00:24:07.870
serve as a Bronsted-Lowry
base.

00:24:07.870 --> 00:24:12.140
We know that water, because it
has hydroxyl in it, has to

00:24:12.140 --> 00:24:12.910
satisfy this.

00:24:12.910 --> 00:24:13.970
So let's take a look.

00:24:13.970 --> 00:24:16.940
H20 we can do similarly.

00:24:16.940 --> 00:24:18.190
Oxygen.

00:24:18.190 --> 00:24:21.050
It's got 6 electrons, 2 are in
the, bonds and we have 2

00:24:21.050 --> 00:24:22.520
non-bonding pairs.

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:26.380
So then when we attach
proton here, we make

00:24:26.380 --> 00:24:29.050
something called hydronium.

00:24:29.050 --> 00:24:32.390
We make hydronium ion.

00:24:32.390 --> 00:24:34.750
So it's a little fancier than
just saying, I've got this

00:24:34.750 --> 00:24:37.960
naked proton with no electrons
swimming around in water.

00:24:37.960 --> 00:24:41.340
In fact, it's more coordinated
like this.

00:24:41.340 --> 00:24:44.180
H30 plus, and while we're
in the neighborhood, we

00:24:44.180 --> 00:24:44.870
might as well show.

00:24:44.870 --> 00:24:46.930
This is sp3 hybridized.

00:24:46.930 --> 00:24:51.190
We've got one, two, three,
four orbitals.

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:52.560
Hydrogen's on three.

00:24:52.560 --> 00:24:56.180
It's got a net charge of
plus 1, and lone pair

00:24:56.180 --> 00:24:57.620
on the fourth side.

00:24:57.620 --> 00:25:01.680
So there's the structure
of hydronium.

00:25:01.680 --> 00:25:04.310
And we can now write
the equation.

00:25:04.310 --> 00:25:14.050
We can say H20 liquid plus
H20 liquid gives me H3O

00:25:14.050 --> 00:25:18.520
plus, plus OH minus.

00:25:18.520 --> 00:25:22.520
So this is now the
self-ionization or

00:25:22.520 --> 00:25:23.720
self-dissociation reaction.

00:25:23.720 --> 00:25:26.520
So now I can pair
these as well.

00:25:26.520 --> 00:25:28.540
I can yoke these.

00:25:28.540 --> 00:25:29.890
I have acid-base pair.

00:25:29.890 --> 00:25:36.100
So this is acid here, and the
conjugate base is water, H20.

00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:39.180
Hydroxyl, we know, has
to be a base, and its

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:41.720
conjugate acid is water.

00:25:41.720 --> 00:25:44.100
So you see, in the same
equation, same place, same

00:25:44.100 --> 00:25:48.340
time, water is acting as both
acid and base relative to

00:25:48.340 --> 00:25:50.440
these two species.

00:25:50.440 --> 00:25:55.080
And so we call such a such a
compound that acts as both

00:25:55.080 --> 00:25:57.360
acid and base, we call
it amphipathic.

00:26:01.930 --> 00:26:04.310
Has two moods.

00:26:04.310 --> 00:26:06.082
You know, amphi, like
in amphitheater.

00:26:06.082 --> 00:26:07.870
Have you ever seen
a Roman theater?

00:26:07.870 --> 00:26:09.575
It looks like this from
the top down.

00:26:09.575 --> 00:26:12.410
It's got all this, you know,
like this, and all the people

00:26:12.410 --> 00:26:14.690
are here, and there's
the stage up here.

00:26:14.690 --> 00:26:22.440
But if I make a theater in the
round, that is amphitheater.

00:26:22.440 --> 00:26:26.120
Or as it's commonly
mispronounced, ampitheater.

00:26:26.120 --> 00:26:28.750
3091ers do not say ampitheater,
they say

00:26:28.750 --> 00:26:29.810
amphitheater.

00:26:29.810 --> 00:26:33.130
So this reaction here is
self-dissociation.

00:26:33.130 --> 00:26:33.400
Right?

00:26:33.400 --> 00:26:38.300
This reaction is
self-dissociation of water.

00:26:38.300 --> 00:26:41.980
Or because we're forming
ions, it's also called

00:26:41.980 --> 00:26:43.230
self-ionization.

00:26:48.260 --> 00:26:51.110
Self-dissociation or
self-ionization of water.

00:26:51.110 --> 00:26:55.710
Now, turns out that the
chemical's power of H3O plus

00:26:55.710 --> 00:26:57.620
and OH minus is very high.

00:26:57.620 --> 00:27:00.350
So this reaction doesn't go
very far to the right.

00:27:00.350 --> 00:27:04.690
The amount of the dissociation
is tiny, and to be specific,

00:27:04.690 --> 00:27:09.790
at 25 degrees C, the amount
of, if you take deionized,

00:27:09.790 --> 00:27:13.530
deaerated water, absolutely
pure and pristine.

00:27:13.530 --> 00:27:18.120
