strong acid or not?

00:41:22.260 --> 00:41:26.590
It's how willing HF is
to give up its H.

00:41:26.590 --> 00:41:28.710
But its H is tightly bound.

00:41:28.710 --> 00:41:32.440
So oddly enough, in HF, you
don't give up much of the H.

00:41:32.440 --> 00:41:33.880
HF is over here.

00:41:33.880 --> 00:41:35.170
It's less than one.

00:41:35.170 --> 00:41:36.500
It's a weak acid.

00:41:36.500 --> 00:41:38.310
HCl is a pretty strong acid.

00:41:38.310 --> 00:41:43.020
If you want to go heavy-duty,
HBr and HI are even stronger

00:41:43.020 --> 00:41:46.630
acids, because they have a
weaker hold on the hydrogen

00:41:46.630 --> 00:41:49.600
within them, so they
are much, much more

00:41:49.600 --> 00:41:51.760
generous proton donors.

00:41:51.760 --> 00:41:53.490
So you can see that from there.

00:41:53.490 --> 00:41:54.990
OK.

00:41:54.990 --> 00:41:58.110
So what's the takeaway
message here?

00:41:58.110 --> 00:42:07.010
The takeaway message is that
equal acid concentration does

00:42:07.010 --> 00:42:08.760
not mean equal acid strength.

00:42:08.760 --> 00:42:11.210
You have to be mediated
by the Ka.

00:42:11.210 --> 00:42:14.420
Equal acid concentration,
which means, how

00:42:14.420 --> 00:42:16.010
much did you dissolve?

00:42:16.010 --> 00:42:22.510
Does not equal acid strength.

00:42:22.510 --> 00:42:23.510
And what's the reason?

00:42:23.510 --> 00:42:26.140
Because equal acid
concentration, this is a

00:42:26.140 --> 00:42:30.090
function of solubility, whereas
this is a function of

00:42:30.090 --> 00:42:31.090
dissociation.

00:42:31.090 --> 00:42:34.160
So many dissolve,
few dissociate.

00:42:34.160 --> 00:42:34.830
How about that?

00:42:34.830 --> 00:42:37.600
There's a nice tagline
you can use.

00:42:37.600 --> 00:42:39.180
Use that at a party
this weekend.

00:42:39.180 --> 00:42:41.130
Many dissolve, but
few dissociate.

00:42:41.130 --> 00:42:41.450
All right.

00:42:41.450 --> 00:42:43.120
Now I want to go very,
very high.

00:42:43.120 --> 00:42:44.590
Big concept, all right?

00:42:44.590 --> 00:42:48.330
Last definition of acid-base
comes from the United States.

00:42:48.330 --> 00:42:48.450
G.

00:42:48.450 --> 00:42:48.740
N.

00:42:48.740 --> 00:42:50.820
Lewis.

00:42:50.820 --> 00:42:51.150
Same G.

00:42:51.150 --> 00:42:51.370
N.

00:42:51.370 --> 00:42:55.310
Lewis who gave us the Lewis
cross and dot structures,

00:42:55.310 --> 00:42:58.080
covalent bonding, didn't
stop inventing.

00:42:58.080 --> 00:43:01.280
So we're going to put U.S.A.,
with a Chevrolet out in

00:43:01.280 --> 00:43:02.470
California.

00:43:02.470 --> 00:43:03.190
And what did G.

00:43:03.190 --> 00:43:03.430
N.

00:43:03.430 --> 00:43:04.550
Lewis tell us?

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:08.950
He said, I want to extend the
Bronsted-Lowry concept.

00:43:08.950 --> 00:43:10.485
But you know, let me give
you an analogy.

00:43:10.485 --> 00:43:12.140
Have you ever stood
on a bridge and

00:43:12.140 --> 00:43:14.150
watched the traffic go?

00:43:14.150 --> 00:43:16.750
You see it starts from a stop
sign or a traffic light.

00:43:16.750 --> 00:43:20.140
Light turns green, the first car
pulls away, the second car

00:43:20.140 --> 00:43:23.020
pulls away, the third
car pulls away.

00:43:23.020 --> 00:43:25.370
The other way you can look at
it is, when the first car

00:43:25.370 --> 00:43:27.600
pulls away, there's
a car vacancy.

00:43:27.600 --> 00:43:31.150
And instead of watching the cars
go from right to left,

00:43:31.150 --> 00:43:34.440
watch the car vacancy move
from left to right.

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:35.980
And the two are linked.

00:43:35.980 --> 00:43:39.030
And point of fact, if you're
the fourth car from the

00:43:39.030 --> 00:43:40.630
traffic light, light
turns green and you

00:43:40.630 --> 00:43:42.350
hit the horn, why?

00:43:42.350 --> 00:43:43.350
You can't drive.

00:43:43.350 --> 00:43:46.020
You have to drive only into a
car vacancy, and it takes time

00:43:46.020 --> 00:43:48.130
for the car vacancy
to get to you.

00:43:48.130 --> 00:43:52.340
When the rate of vacancy flux is
not matched by the rate of

00:43:52.340 --> 00:43:55.340
car flux, then we have a
collision, and then we

00:43:55.340 --> 00:43:56.220
exchange papers.

00:43:56.220 --> 00:43:58.570
So it's a mass transport
problem.

00:43:58.570 --> 00:43:59.315
So now what G.

00:43:59.315 --> 00:43:59.500
N.

00:43:59.500 --> 00:44:05.620
Lewis said was, instead of
looking at this reaction as a

00:44:05.620 --> 00:44:10.470
proton transfer reaction, and
looking at proton attachment,

00:44:10.470 --> 00:44:13.680
or proton acquisition, he said,
why don't we look at

00:44:13.680 --> 00:44:17.390
this from the other side
of the relationship?

00:44:17.390 --> 00:44:20.860
And so he said, let's look at
something like, for example,

00:44:20.860 --> 00:44:22.640
we've got NH3 here.

00:44:22.640 --> 00:44:27.910
So let's put the N with
the 2 electrons.

00:44:27.910 --> 00:44:31.300
And we've been talking about
this from the perspective of

00:44:31.300 --> 00:44:34.980
the bond being formed
here through the

00:44:34.980 --> 00:44:37.360
acquisition of the proton.

00:44:37.360 --> 00:44:40.790
Lewis said, I can view this from
the other perspective,

00:44:40.790 --> 00:44:42.490
and say, I'm going to
view it from the

00:44:42.490 --> 00:44:43.850
perspective of the nitrogen.

00:44:43.850 --> 00:44:46.620
From the perspective of the
nitrogen, this reaction

00:44:46.620 --> 00:44:51.690
represents the donation
of the electron pair.

00:44:51.690 --> 00:44:53.440
A very high concept.

00:44:53.440 --> 00:44:57.890
So this base is not about
proton attachment.

00:44:57.890 --> 00:45:01.390
It's about donating an
electronic pair.

00:45:01.390 --> 00:45:04.270
So let's get that down, because
that's really good.

00:45:04.270 --> 00:45:08.400
So I'm going to say something
that's a base looks like this.

00:45:08.400 --> 00:45:09.840
This is what a base is.

00:45:09.840 --> 00:45:11.920
It's a lone pair.

00:45:11.920 --> 00:45:15.355
This is electron pair,
very high level base.

00:45:18.130 --> 00:45:20.900
And what's the proton give us?

00:45:20.900 --> 00:45:22.520
What we're doing, is
we're talking about

00:45:22.520 --> 00:45:24.430
electrons and donation.

00:45:24.430 --> 00:45:27.990
So what's this other thing
in that same category?

00:45:27.990 --> 00:45:33.740
An electron pair can match
up with an empty orbital.

00:45:33.740 --> 00:45:36.110
That's the only place electron
pairs can go.

00:45:36.110 --> 00:45:37.840
They go to the empty orbitals.

00:45:37.840 --> 00:45:41.060
So electron pair is a base,
and this is just a circle

00:45:41.060 --> 00:45:42.410
around nothing.

00:45:42.410 --> 00:45:42.910
OK?

00:45:42.910 --> 00:45:44.170
This is nothing.

00:45:44.170 --> 00:45:46.050
But it's a special
kind of nothing.

00:45:46.050 --> 00:45:47.510
This is called a
vacant orbital.

00:45:52.660 --> 00:45:56.150
And I'm going to call a vacant
orbital an acid, in the most

00:45:56.150 --> 00:45:57.840
general sense.

00:45:57.840 --> 00:46:00.220
So now I'm going to take an
electron pair plus vacant

00:46:00.220 --> 00:46:03.700
orbital, and what did they
react to give me?

00:46:03.700 --> 00:46:06.990
Covalent bond.

00:46:06.990 --> 00:46:08.035
You'd expect that from G.

00:46:08.035 --> 00:46:08.240
N.

00:46:08.240 --> 00:46:12.600
Lewis, because G.

00:46:12.600 --> 00:46:12.960
N.

00:46:12.960 --> 00:46:14.570
Lewis enunciated covalency.

00:46:14.570 --> 00:46:15.873
That's why you'd expect
it from G.

00:46:15.873 --> 00:46:15.976
N.

00:46:15.976 --> 00:46:16.340
Lewis.

00:46:16.340 --> 00:46:19.750
So this is, vacant orbital
plus electron pair gives

00:46:19.750 --> 00:46:20.820
covalent bond.

00:46:20.820 --> 00:46:22.430
Very high level.

00:46:22.430 --> 00:46:23.450
Very high level.

00:46:23.450 --> 00:46:25.190
So what is a base?

00:46:25.190 --> 00:46:31.080
A base is now not just
a proton acceptor.

00:46:31.080 --> 00:46:38.040
It's an electron pair donor,
and the acid is an electron

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:39.290
pair acceptor.

00:46:42.100 --> 00:46:44.130
So now there's no
chemistry here.

00:46:44.130 --> 00:46:46.280
No chemical identities.

00:46:46.280 --> 00:46:49.190
Which means, I can
even go from--

00:46:49.190 --> 00:46:50.620
I don't even have to
be in solution.

00:46:50.620 --> 00:46:52.240
I don't have to be
in a liquid.

00:46:52.240 --> 00:46:54.670
This could be a gas
and a solid.

00:46:54.670 --> 00:46:56.080
Could be a gas plus a gas.

00:46:56.080 --> 00:46:57.790
So this is, like, Darwinian.

00:46:57.790 --> 00:46:59.940
You know, we've come out of the
primordial ooze, and now

00:46:59.940 --> 00:47:03.310
we can fly, because we can
talk about any chemical

00:47:03.310 --> 00:47:04.480
reaction we want.

00:47:04.480 --> 00:47:06.820
Any state of matter.

00:47:06.820 --> 00:47:08.590
It's fantastic.

00:47:08.590 --> 00:47:09.680
Absolutely fantastic.

00:47:09.680 --> 00:47:13.210
So here, let me do one
last color drawing.

00:47:13.210 --> 00:47:14.990
We want to do this one here.

00:47:14.990 --> 00:47:18.030
This is Lewis and the
biggest concept.

00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:19.570
So we're going to
go like this.

00:47:19.570 --> 00:47:23.120
Base like this.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:26.620
Base with its lone
pair hanging out

00:47:26.620 --> 00:47:31.110
plus acid gives us--

00:47:31.110 --> 00:47:31.760
three colors.

00:47:31.760 --> 00:47:32.370
This is great.

00:47:32.370 --> 00:47:35.100
We've got all this colored
chalk, it's Friday,

00:47:35.100 --> 00:47:36.070
what could be better.

00:47:36.070 --> 00:47:37.680
All right.

00:47:37.680 --> 00:47:44.470
So now we're going to end up
with A, B, there it is.

00:47:44.470 --> 00:47:46.340
This is the Lewis concept.

00:47:46.340 --> 00:47:53.400
Lewis acid-base concept.

00:47:53.400 --> 00:47:54.310
In the broadest thing.

00:47:54.310 --> 00:47:55.460
Now I'm going to show
you an example of

00:47:55.460 --> 00:47:57.090
how you can use this.

00:47:57.090 --> 00:47:58.000
I'm not going to stop here.

00:47:58.000 --> 00:47:59.410
OK, let's go.

00:47:59.410 --> 00:47:59.720
All right.

00:47:59.720 --> 00:48:01.240
So we're going to talk
about acid rain

00:48:01.240 --> 00:48:02.870
from burning of coal.

00:48:02.870 --> 00:48:05.210
You know, about half of the
electric power in this country

00:48:05.210 --> 00:48:09.930
comes from burning coal, and
coal contains about 1% sulfur.

00:48:09.930 --> 00:48:14.290
You can purify it of sulfur, but
it takes money to do so.

00:48:14.290 --> 00:48:16.640
A ton of coal will give you
about 25 million British

00:48:16.640 --> 00:48:20.130
thermal units, and that's the
number in SI units and joules.

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:23.890
So 3 tons of coal will give
you 1 megawatt per day.

00:48:23.890 --> 00:48:26.070
By the way, it takes about
one gram of uranium

00:48:26.070 --> 00:48:26.880
to do the same thing.

00:48:26.880 --> 00:48:28.170
So someday, when you're
sitting there as a

00:48:28.170 --> 00:48:31.450
policymaker, you've got a choice
of 3 tons of coal or

00:48:31.450 --> 00:48:34.290
one gram of uranium, keep
this fact in mind.

00:48:34.290 --> 00:48:37.690
A 10 megawatt plant burns
30 tons of coal per day,

00:48:37.690 --> 00:48:41.160
containing a third of a ton of
sulphur, which makes 2/3 of a

00:48:41.160 --> 00:48:43.230
ton of SO2.

00:48:43.230 --> 00:48:46.600
And SO2 is a precursor
to acid rain.

00:48:46.600 --> 00:48:50.520
Now we can reduce that SO2
emissions by reacting SO2 with

00:48:50.520 --> 00:48:53.140
a lime, CaO, according
to this reaction, to

00:48:53.140 --> 00:48:55.610
make calcium sulfite.

00:48:55.610 --> 00:48:58.170
And now I'm going to
bring in this.

00:48:58.170 --> 00:48:59.430
Lewis.

00:48:59.430 --> 00:49:02.390
Oh, here's from your textbook,
there's the scrubbers with the

00:49:02.390 --> 00:49:05.010
calcium oxide, and water
missed, and so on, and

00:49:05.010 --> 00:49:08.810
eventually they trap the SO2.

00:49:08.810 --> 00:49:10.210
They do nothing to the CO2.

00:49:10.210 --> 00:49:13.510
So all the CO2 is going up.

00:49:13.510 --> 00:49:16.060
So here's calcium oxide,
which is a solid.

00:49:16.060 --> 00:49:17.100
It's lime.

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:19.990
You know, stuff you sprinkle
on football fields.

00:49:19.990 --> 00:49:22.460
And this is SO2, and it's got
this structure with the

00:49:22.460 --> 00:49:24.750
resident bond double single.

00:49:24.750 --> 00:49:27.940
The oxygen here acts the
way it did in the

00:49:27.940 --> 00:49:29.490
glasses, as a modifier.

00:49:29.490 --> 00:49:31.580
It goes in and breaks this
double bond, and now we have

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:33.900
three single bonds.

00:49:33.900 --> 00:49:37.090
So we can look at this
from Lewis acid-base.

00:49:37.090 --> 00:49:39.960
You know, calcium oxides,
electron pair donor.

00:49:39.960 --> 00:49:42.880
If it's an electron pair
donor, it's a base.

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:43.720
So it's a base.

00:49:43.720 --> 00:49:47.250
And you know SO2 better be an
acid, or your theory is nuts,

00:49:47.250 --> 00:49:49.340
because SO2 is a precursor
to acid rain.

00:49:49.340 --> 00:49:50.670
So it has to be an acid.

00:49:50.670 --> 00:49:52.450
It's an electronic
pair acceptor,

00:49:52.450 --> 00:49:53.390
which is what we said.

00:49:53.390 --> 00:49:54.660
It's an electron
pair acceptor.

00:49:54.660 --> 00:49:58.020
So this is a Lewis acid-base
reaction that

00:49:58.020 --> 00:49:59.770
is a gas-solid reaction.

00:49:59.770 --> 00:50:03.050
So we started with aqueous
solutions, and we end up

00:50:03.050 --> 00:50:05.790
generalizing all of these
types of reactions.

00:50:05.790 --> 00:50:07.360
So that's pretty good.

