00:50:22.790 --> 00:50:24.250
Scheele and Priestley.

00:50:24.250 --> 00:50:26.310
This is a play, if you've
got the little bit

00:50:26.310 --> 00:50:27.220
of time this weekend.

00:50:27.220 --> 00:50:28.130
You might try reading it.

00:50:28.130 --> 00:50:30.760
This is Carl Djerassi and Roald
Hoffman, both Nobel

00:50:30.760 --> 00:50:32.440
Prize winners in Chemistry.

00:50:32.440 --> 00:50:33.260
Not the same year.

00:50:33.260 --> 00:50:36.340
They won independent Nobel
Prizes, and actually speak to

00:50:36.340 --> 00:50:39.010
each other, and they
collaborated on this play.

00:50:39.010 --> 00:50:41.000
Here's the setup, the premise.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:43.150
The premise of the play is
that the Nobel committee

00:50:43.150 --> 00:50:47.380
decides to give Nobel
Prizes retrograde.

00:50:47.380 --> 00:50:48.600
Before 1901.

00:50:48.600 --> 00:50:51.740
You see, you can't get a Nobel
Prize posthumously.

00:50:51.740 --> 00:50:54.070
You've got to do something
great, and you've got to keep

00:50:54.070 --> 00:50:56.670
on living until you
get the prize.

00:50:56.670 --> 00:50:58.590
So they decided they're going
to go backwards, you know,

00:50:58.590 --> 00:51:01.250
maybe give prizes to people
like, I don't know, Maxwell or

00:51:01.250 --> 00:51:02.800
Faraday or whatever.

00:51:02.800 --> 00:51:05.370
And they decide, it should be
simple in the old days.

00:51:05.370 --> 00:51:07.790
Because we didn't have all this
dog-eat-dog competition

00:51:07.790 --> 00:51:10.530
in science, and big grants,
and corporate interests.

00:51:10.530 --> 00:51:11.790
Should be simple.

00:51:11.790 --> 00:51:17.670
Until they hit the Nobel Prize
for the discovery of oxygen.

00:51:17.670 --> 00:51:20.000
And then they hit the wall with
these three different

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:21.080
competitors.

00:51:21.080 --> 00:51:24.120
And so the story goes that the
three competitors and their

00:51:24.120 --> 00:51:26.440
wives end up in Stockholm,
and the

00:51:26.440 --> 00:51:28.100
interactions the take place.

00:51:28.100 --> 00:51:31.350
And it's really fascinating,
because you have Lavoisier,

00:51:31.350 --> 00:51:34.260
who was the political
conservative but the chemical

00:51:34.260 --> 00:51:39.320
radical, Priestley, who was the
chemical radical but the

00:51:39.320 --> 00:51:40.650
political conservative--

00:51:40.650 --> 00:51:41.710
by the way, Lavoisier.

00:51:41.710 --> 00:51:43.190
You know how he died?

00:51:43.190 --> 00:51:45.800
He was guillotined during
the French revolution.

00:51:45.800 --> 00:51:48.630
And people think it's because
he was a tax collector.

00:51:48.630 --> 00:51:49.450
Not true.

00:51:49.450 --> 00:51:51.210
He was a tax collector.

00:51:51.210 --> 00:51:55.070
The real reason is Marat, who
was one of the chief justices

00:51:55.070 --> 00:51:59.220
of the Jacobin terror, was also
a scientist. And around

00:51:59.220 --> 00:52:03.380
1740, Marat had submitted an
article for publication, and

00:52:03.380 --> 00:52:04.430
it was rejected.

00:52:04.430 --> 00:52:08.710
And Lavoisier was on the
editorial board.

00:52:08.710 --> 00:52:11.910
And so sometimes when I get an
article to review, and I have

00:52:11.910 --> 00:52:15.680
to give it a negative review,
I think about this story.

